`submission.json` uses per-seed top-level keys (e.g., `val_bpb_seed1337`, `bytes_seed42`) instead of the `seeds` + `seed_results` structure used by most other track_10min_16mb records (e.g., `records/track_10min_16mb/2026-03-20_Int6_MLP3x_SmearGate_BigramHash_MuonWD_SWA/submission.json`). If there’s downstream tooling expecting the common schema, this record may not get picked up correctly. Consider switching to the standard shape (`val_loss`, `val_bpb`, `val_loss_std`, `val_bpb_std`, `seeds`, `seed_results`, plus `bytes_total`/`bytes_code`).
```suggestion
  "val_loss": 1.8886,
  "val_loss_std": 0.0007,
  "val_bpb": 1.1186,
  "val_bpb_std": 0.0006,
  "seeds": [
    1337,
    42,
    7
  ],
  "seed_results": {
    "1337": {
      "val_bpb": 1.1189,
      "val_loss": 1.8891,
      "bytes": 15945134
    },
    "42": {
      "val_bpb": 1.1189,
      "val_loss": 1.8891,
      "bytes": 15947742
    },
    "7": {
      "val_bpb": 1.1179,
